&nbsp;
"We are heading towards 2.7 degrees of increase >: It is still roviously high, and the way to go to reach our shared goal of 1.5 (grades) in this century is long and steep of obstacles," he said opening the 60th meeting of the subsidiary bodies of the conference on the climate of Bonn.> The two-day conference, attended by about 6,000 participants including national representatives, NGOs and civil society activists, aims to promote progress and prepare decisions for the approval of the next COP29, which will be held in the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, next November.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;Stiell underlined that why &nbsp; all parts of the Paris Agreement are set up, it is necessary to carry out "serious progress" > especially on the financing front. "I urge you to move from the draft to the real options for a new collective objective quantified on climate finance, because &nbsp; we cannot afford to get to Baku with too much work yet to do," he said.
&nbsp;
So far, it has remembered, only 57 countries have developed a plan? "When we meet again in Baku, this number should be increased considerably. We need all countries to have a plan by 2025 and proceed with its implementation by 2030," he said. Although, he admitted, "there are many obstacles to overcome and in some days you can be tempted to get discouraged" in the fight against climate change, much has been achieved in the last three decades through this process called by the UN in Bonn: "Without international cooperation promoted by the UN we would be condemned to global warming up to 5 degrees."
